I think you should briefly add what X/ and /X mean as cells, you jump right into an example without explaining what they are.

Getting back to my previous post, I think this should be a hard puzzle only, because backtracking can solve every example fairly easily (as we saw together). Imo a very hard version would require the user to go into proper constraints solving, using matrix reduction for example. A good example of that is the haunted manor : https://www.codingame.com/training/expert/haunted-manor (check it out if you haven't, it's a great puzzle :))

2 examples of trimmed down options to filter useless moves :
- If a constraint only has 2 unset values remaining, then you know they both add up to the rest, so you can write "for loop i = 1; i < rest / 2" and add both i and 'rest - i' as options, assuming they are both available (if one is not, drop both).
- If you have more than 2 unset values, say 4 for example, then you know the other 3 will add up to a strict minimum of 6 (3 +2 +1) so your for loop can be capped at rest - 6.
